\section{Programming language}
It is your choice.
\begin{itemize}
\item R
\begin{itemize}
\item advantage: used in statistics, good at simulations, free (like
our book,i.e. comercal version is called S+)
\item Disadvantage: steep learning curve.
\end{itemize}
\item JMP
\begin{itemize}
\item  advantage: used in statistics.
\item Disadvantage: not easy to do simulations with.
\end{itemize}
\item spread sheets
\begin{itemize}
\item advantage: easy to use
\item disadvantage: cumbersome
\end{itemize}
\item Mathematica, matlab, maple
\begin{itemize}
\item advantage: also good at mathematics, linear algebra
\item disadvantage: expensive, (octave is free clone of matlab) and
not trivial to learn
\end{itemize}
\item You can also use real programming languages (i.e. C++, java,
basic) if already know them.
\end{itemize}



